In the multivariate regression analysis, the education level of a household head, residence status (i.e., urban or rural) and water source type (i.e. piped or non-piped supplies) were found to be significant on detection of E. coli (≥1 (cfu/100mL)) in drinking water sources, while the wealth variable was not (Table 1
                        .). E. coli was significantly more likely to be detected in drinking water sources collected from (1) households whose heads finished only primary or none of formal education than those finished secondary of higher education (adjusted odds ratio (aOR): 1.98, 95%CI: 1.15–3.41), (2) rural districts than urban districts (aOR: 2.43, 95%CI: 1.32–4.47) and (3) non-piped water supplies than piped water supplies (aOR: 3.58, 95%CI: 2.09–6.16) (Table 2
                        ). For detection of higher level of E. coli contamination (i.e.≥100 (cfu/100mL)), access to unimproved sanitation facility and presence of septic tank or other faecal waste disposal area within 10m from the water source showed 1.7 times (aOR: 1.74, 95%CI: 1.10–2.76) and 1.5 times (aOR: 1.49, 95%CI: 0.98–2.25) higher likelihood of detecting E. coli more than or equal to 100 (cfu/100mL), respectively, in addition to a significant association with wealth tertile. There is no statistical evidence that improved water sources decrease the odds of detection of E. coli (≥1 cfu/100mL); nor for the very high risk E. coli category (≥100 cfu/100mL) in DWS.
